Is there a black box in your car?
While American road designers are trying to find money to repair a loose highway system, many are beginning to see the solution in a small black box carefully built on your car's dashboard.
These devices, which track every mile a motorist passes and convey this information to officials, are at the heart of a controversial attempt to modernize America's outdated highway financing system undertaken by Washington and state planners.
Usually, the boring highway planning arena unexpectedly gave rise to intense debates and colorful alliances.
Libertarians joined environmental groups in lobbying for the government's right to use small boxes to track the number of miles you drive, and perhaps even where you drive them, and then use this information in tax accounts.
The tea party movement is in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of questions about privacy.
Although Congress cannot yet agree whether to continue or not, several states are not going to wait.
They wonder how, over the next decade, we can move to a system in which drivers pay for every mile of the road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already tested these black boxes, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is indeed necessary for our country.
"This is not a matter on which we may have the right to choose," said Hassan Ihrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to start tracking the state of miles passed by every California motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology for that is already in place.
This need is compounded by the lack of funds from the Government's Highway Foundation, funded by taxes that Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans don't buy as much petrol as they used to.
Cars drive more than one gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased for 20 years.
Politicians don't want to raise the tax by even one cent at high gasoline prices.
"The gas tax simply cannot be saved," said Lee Mannitch, a transport policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
In his staff, 500 tracking devices had recently been installed on vehicles to test the pardon system.
"This will be the best alternative in the long run," he said.
The nerds call it a soft user's pay.
Not surprisingly, this idea attracts urban liberals, as taxes can change the nature of travel to reduce road congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planners in California look to the system in developing strategies to meet the targets set by the state's ambitious anti-global warming laws.
However, House member Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the Chamber's transport committee, said that he too saw the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market adherents at the Reason Foundation are also thrilled to make drivers pay for every mile.
"It's not just a tax that's going to go to a black hole," said Adrian Moore, Vice President for Political Affairs Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
This movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in 2011 called on Congress to move towards a mercy payment.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would involve about 10,000 cars.
However, the leaders of the House of Representatives rejected the proposal because of the concerns of rural legislators representing voters, who often had to travel many miles to work or to the city in daily life.
Several states and cities, however, are on their own.
The greatest enthusiasm is in Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are involved in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers are about to pay the state for miles of running instead of a gas tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
It's being considered in New York.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with the participation of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes transport departments from 17 states of the eastern coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is exploring how they can make these changes.
This concept has not been universally accepted.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer vehicles were recently equipped with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could monitor every move.
"The concern about "big brother" and similar things is a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, who is in charge of strategy and performance management in the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't what people wanted.
When the trials were well under way, the Nevada branch of the American Civil Liberties Union warned on its website, "It will not be difficult to turn these devices into full-scale tracking devices."
There is no need to create a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to keep records of the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of several states where there is a difficult search for low-cost technology that would allow the state authorities to keep track of the miles driven by the car, but without information about the place and time.
If you can do it, Han said, society will feel more comfortable.
Searching for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Originally, this company did not assist in collecting state taxes.
It sought to enter the developing market for the form of car insurance in which drivers pay on the basis of mileage.
But the devices she's testing attract road designers because they don't use GPS and provide a limited amount of information periodically downloaded by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't track their speed and track their location," said Ryan Morrison, executive director of True Mileage.
There were some big mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are far less expensive and less obsessive ways to do so.
In Oregon, designers experiment with providing drivers with different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can totally abandon the device by deciding instead to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state pass.
In other places, they hope to sell the idea to the alert public, forcing devices to do more, not less.
In New York, transport officials are seeking to develop a tax device that will also accept parking counter fees, provide "pays as you drive" insurance, and collect a real-time speed data pool from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Automobiles will bring in the benefits that will be offered to them," says the urban design document.
Some transport system designers, however, wonder whether all the talk of a pardon is simply a huge distraction.
At the San Francisco Gulf City Transportation Commission, officials say that Congress could easily overturn the bankruptcy of the trust fund for highway construction by raising taxes on gasoline.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be imposed on hybrid car drivers and others whose vehicles do not use much petrol to pay their fair share.
"There is no need for radical surgical intervention when all you have to do is take aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, director of the Law and Public Relations Commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a lot of other things.
