Russia Without Car Pollution
Attempts to address the transport problems of major cities have been made in most mega-cities of the world since the second half of the twentieth century.
These were usually either the redevelopment and extension of the highways or attempts to reduce the demand for road travel, the number of vehicles and the time they were used.
The case of Singapore is well known, where strict quotas have been introduced for the growth of private cars and the right to purchase them is purchased at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced fees for entry into the city centre.
In Germany, for example in Hamburg and Stuttgart, so-called green zones are introduced, allowing only vehicles with a certain eco-class to enter, using also high-quality fuels (including biofuels or electric vehicles).
The Beijing Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved in 2012 a “five-year clean air plan” with a total cost of about 250 billion yuan (about $40 billion).
According to IA, Director of Transport Pollution Control, Beijing City Environmental Protection Bureau Lee Kunscheng, the primary goal of the five-year-old is to reduce leading air pollutants by 20-35 per cent by 2017, to increase the number of private cars to no more than 6 million (now 5.2 million), and to increase fuel use by no more than 5 per cent per vehicle.
According to the agency, cars in Beijing are now responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
The main measures of the programme include limiting the use of road transport as well as introducing additional taxes for car owners.
Among other things, the city's green five-year-old measures include an accelerated transition to Euro-fuel standards compared with the rest of the country, the introduction of a local eco-standard and car and fuel labelling system, a restriction on the entry of cars into the central part of the city, a ban on the use of obsolete vehicles (in addition to the introduction of incentive financial programmes to replace old vehicles with hybrid or electric vehicles), the development of electric transport (including public and official transport), and the development of public transport (including high-speed transport).
Car innovations in Beijing also include the ban on all private cars to drive within the fifth transport ring (six in total in the capital PRC) one day a week (relevant information is contained in the vehicle licence plate) and the issue of lottery-based car registrations (e.g. in 2011, the first year of the lottery, the total number of permits for registration of private cars in Beijing was only one third of 2010).
According to the current State programme “Environmental Protection 2012-2020”, the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should decrease to 128 (in 2012, there were 138).
According to the Ministry of Nature, in 2011 “mobile sources” accounted for 41 per cent of all emissions of pollutants to the urban atmosphere.
In Moscow, for example, car emissions are ten times higher than industrial emissions and in St. Petersburg, nine times higher.
The Russian Federation is just beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
The Director of the Institute for Transport Economics and Transport Policy of the HSE, Mikhail Blinkin, believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at curbing the demand for road travel are notoriously unpopular, and can be adopted by society only if they are fully universal.
In the case of Moscow, there is a unique problem related to the structure of its vehicle fleet, where there are two clusters of weakly sensitive to any regulatory impact - service and personal cars, as well as cars of “privileged” users with a total of at least 200,000 (about 5% of Moscow's total fleet).
In the recent period, urbanists from the ECOM centre in St. Petersburg prepared a study analysing the balance of urban areas between residential development, road surface and the number of vehicles.
The main findings of the researchers are that the city centre is provided with roads half as much as required, and most of the motorists living in the centre do not use cars every day, leaving them for long periods of time in parking or simply in the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build car storage facilities rather than to expand, but to reduce the carriageway (to make the streets more friendly to pedestrians) and to restrict the use and location of personal transport within the security area of the historic centre (a total area of about 3,212 hectares covering a number of central areas of the city).
