The speech gene turned out to be a synapse booster.
Scientists from Johns Hopkins University and Mount Sinai Medical School found a protein that enables Foxp2's "gen of speech" to perform its function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, and the magazine's website can read its short contents.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known genome whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 with the discovery of a family of several people who could not pronounce words correctly and sometimes did not even understand each other themselves.
Scientists found that family members had been disabled by the Foxp2 gene, but how it performed its function remained unknown.
In a new study, biologists have shown that at least part of their Foxp2 functions act as a catalyst for the formation of new synapses in the brain area associated with speech formation.
He does it through another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered by the search for factors that stimulate synapses.
SRPX2 proved to be one of the 10 similar genes found by the authors, with only Foxp2 on his activity.
What SRPX2 does affect vocalization, scientists confirmed in a mouse experiment.
When the activity of the gene was artificially reduced in animals, they screamed less when separated from their mother.
If the gene activity was restored, the frequency of the sound produced was restored.
Previously, mice also showed a connection to the vocalization of Foxp2.
Animals who were injected with a human copy of the gene were fed more actively and at a lower frequency than regular mice.
So far, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, consequently, its SRPX2 is linked to purely “mechanical” characteristics of sound formation or more subtle processes.
