According to The New York Times, the closest advisors to President Barack Obama were secretly considering replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton on the 2012 electoral list.
This discovery is the brightest sensation of everyone's expected book Mark Halperin and John Hailemann on the 2012 campaign "The Stacks Doubled: The Game Changed 2012".
The Times edition received a copy of the forthcoming book and reported on Thursday evening that the president's closest aides had conducted "large-scale research in focus groups and public opinion polls in late 2011" to assess whether Biden's exclusion could help raise the waning hopes for Obama's re-election.
According to political columnist The Times Jonathan Martin, the book provides a detailed description of the attempt by senior election staff and White House officials, namely former White House Chief of Staff Bill Daily, to assess the impact of the election of former Secretary Clinton as Vice President.
The possible replacement was a secret, carefully guarded in the Chicago Election Headquarters and the Oval Office.
Only six of the president's closest advisers — including Daley, former head of Obama's campaign staff Jim Messinu, and former White House senior advisers David Axelrod and David Pluff — knew that replacement was under consideration.
The book Stacks doubled claims that Daley was the initiator of an attempt to replace Biden despite their "near personal relationships", but eventually abandoned this step when their data showed that Clinton's addition to the electoral list would not "enhanced Obama's substantial chances."
In an interview with Martin Daily, he confirmed that the administration had indeed considered replacing Biden Clinton.
"I have been active in addressing a lot of things, and it was one of them," Daily said to the newspaper.
You must remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we thought, "Oh, my God, what do we do?"
Although Daley described the study as a "necessary test", Martin told CNN representative Anderson Cooper that the campaign staff had invested enough in exploring whether this step would bring dividends to the vote.
"Pre-elected headquarters don't spend that much money on polls and focus groups unless they take something seriously," Martin said in AC 360.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew that his team was exploring the possibility of replacing.
Martin told CNN that he had asked Daley if his then boss knew about a possible reshuffle.
Although Daley said that he did not think the president "was aware" of a possible replacement, former chief of administration admitted that "possibly", Obama knew.
Martin added that "Staves doubled" does not provide a clear answer to the question whether the political sensing has reached Obama's desk.
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously thought Obama was unaware of research into the possibility of removing Biden from the electoral list.
"Possibly," Martin replied.
