The pawnshop owners in Singapore are doing well while the middle class is experiencing difficulties.
In a pawnshop at the Bendemir mall in Singapore, Janani Amirthaling lays a gold bracelet, ring and earrings to pay for his daughter's schooling.
"My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is invested there," says Ms. Amirthalinga.
Although she earns S$3000 ($2,400) a month as an administrator and her husband also works, the family's monthly income is not enough, she says.
Indeed, demand in various parts of South-East Asia — where household debt is increasing — is such that ValueMax, where it is making its deal, became the third pawnshop registered on Singapore's stock exchange this week.
Credit on jewellery is not just a quick way to get money (S $1,300 in the case of Ms. Amirthaling), but also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Usually, pawnshops in Singapore account for an effective annual interest rate of 17% – just above the 15.4% offered at the United Overseas Bank branch, a local lender with a branch at the same mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require credit or wage proof tests and can issue loans faster than banks.
Therefore, millions of people in the entire region resort to pawnshops because families feel pressure because of the rising cost of living and the rapid increase in household debt and consumer debt.
After five years of sustained growth following the global financial crisis and cheap loans fuelled by free monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families resort to pawnshops to offset the decline in income as their economies slow down.
This week, Standard & Poor's, a rating agency, indicated an increase in the family credit shoulder, mainly due to the rise in mortgages, as a risk factor for Asian banks' creditworthiness.
It stated that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia led the list with 80% of GDP, compared with 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from the technical recession this week.
On Thursday, data showed a continuing decline in exports and in consumer demand.
"The point is that with rising prices, people in the middle and lower part [of the income scale] will seek ways to supplement their income wherever they can," says Song Seng Won, an economist of CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Recorded high gold prices in the past two years have increased the rush with which people pawn their personal belongings as they take the opportunity to get money for their family jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70% of the items laid in the city-state 200 pawnshops are gold products.
People say, "The price of gold looks good, let's pawn the gold chain of the grandmother and get it back next month."
In Thailand, the largest EastyMoney pawnshop operator observed an increase in the number of clients using its offices in recent months, up to 20%.
Growth in the pawnshop business is such that ValueMax, the operator of the Bendemir branch and 15 others in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, executive director of the ValueMax.
The company will finance expansion using 60 per cent of the S$66 million leveraged this week as a result of the listing on Singapore's stock exchange.
While some creditors had been criticized for high interest rates, she said that the pawnshop was not only offering cheaper tariffs than other creditors, nor was it directly increasing debt.
"Clinents mortgage items they already own, and monetizing personal assets does not increase household debt," she says.
The mortgage is gaining increasing public acceptance as a means of obtaining short-term, secured financing.
And the pawnshops are not only used by those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Rich people in Singapore also use ValueMax offices by laying gold bars or Rolex clocks, which can give up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see clients from all walks of life.
"They include wealthy persons who need to borrow short-term money for commercial projects or investments, or small businesses that need to overcome temporary monetary difficulties," said Ms. Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
