Delta and JetBlue were among airlines that had already submitted plans.
" Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the expansion of the use of electronic devices very soon," FAU said.
Passengers are now required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane door closes.
They must not restart them until the plane reaches a height of 10,000 feet and the captain gives "good".
Passengers shall switch off their devices again when the aircraft is down to land and shall not include them until the aircraft is on the ground.
In accordance with the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are adequately protected against electronic interference may allow passengers to use these devices during take-off, landing and steering, stated FAU.
Most new airliners and other aircraft modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional flight attendants, welcomed these changes.
"After the new policy is well implemented (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this), it will be a win-win option," Glading said.
We are frankly tired of being "school on duty" when it comes to this question.
But Internet connections for surfing, email exchanges, text messages, or downloading data will still be banned at a height of less than 10,000 feet, the agency reported.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to aircraft mode.
Thus, there is still no Words with Friends, an intellectual Internet game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when there was a common case: the actor was removed from an American Airlines plane for refusing to turn off the device while the plane was on its way to land.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still have to be put in the luggage room because they can hurt someone if they fly all over the cabin.
Mobile phone calls in flight will also continue to be banned.
The Federal Communications Commission, not the FAU, has regulatory authority over telephone calls.
The FAU may lift the ban on some electronic devices during take-off and landing.
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Council, a national transport safety expert for CBS News, stated that cell phones were still considered a risk.
" Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially interfere with navigation devices, but we know through the FCC that they can interfere with cell towers when the plane is in the air," said Rosenker.
The sectoral advisory committee established by FAU to study this issue recommended last month that the Government allow greater use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure on FAHs has increased to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill argue that there are no valid reasons for bans related to security.
It is also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce restrictions as the use of devices has become widespread.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
FAU began limiting passengers' use of electronic devices in 1966 in response to reports of interference with navigation and communication equipment when passengers began carrying FM radio receivers, high-tech gadgets of that time.
New airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by FAU as resistant to electronic interference.
The airlines have offered passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruise height for several years.
Fixed-wing aircraft modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of liners are adapted to the wider use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, said Wert.
Today's electronic devices usually emit radio signals much lower than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, radiate only minimal signals when scrolling pages.
But the signals become stronger when the devices load or send data.
Among those who sought to reduce restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of the company uploaded an entire airliner with their electronic read devices to read Kindle books and flew on it to check for problems, but never found them.
Members of the FAU Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings as to whether the use of devices posed any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Air Passengers Association stated that he considered interference with the devices to be real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee said that there were only isolated reports from pilots proving that devices could interfere with aviation systems, and most of those messages were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAW allow pilots to require passengers to switch off devices during boarding in reduced visibility.
A group of tourism industry representatives welcomed these changes, calling them a reasonable step towards meeting passengers who are now using many technological devices.
"We are glad that FAU recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and security," said Roger Doe, CEO of the U.S. Tourist Association.
