Scientists have shed light on how the dog's tail moves are linked to her mood.
Earlier studies showed that contented dogs spin their tail to the right (in the dog's view), while troubled dogs wave their tail to the left mostly.
But now scientists say that other members of the dog family can notice and respond to these subtle differences in tailing.
Professor Giorgio Wallortigara, a neurobiologist from Trent University, says, "It is well known that people have left and right sides of the brain in different ways involved in forming agents that cause positive or negative emotions."
Here we tried to look at it from other species as well.
He added that just as in humans, the right side of the brain controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the versatile twisting of the tails of other dogs, researchers watched animals as they watched films about other dogs.
They measured the frequency of animal heartbeats and analyzed their behaviour.
We'll probably soon figure out why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
Professor Wallortigara said, "We showed dogs a video of dogs -- either naturalistic versions or silhouette to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the tail movement and direct the tail more to the left or to the right."
When animals saw that otherwise nothing expressing the dog moved its tail to the right (in terms of the spinning dog's tail), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was leaning predominantly to the left (again in terms of the wading dog's tail), their heartbeat was increasing and they looked anxious.
Professor Wallortigara said he didn't think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience what movements they should worry about and what they should not.
He notes: "If there are several encounters with other dogs and often the wiggling of their tail in one direction is related to more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts on the basis of this experience."
Researchers say that these results can give owners, veterinarians, and trainers a better understanding of the emotions of their animal.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting researcher at Bristol University Veterinary School, said it was not the first study to verify whether left and right sides mattered to dogs.
Last year, a group of scientists from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left if they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if they look at a happy dog.
And in another scholarly paper by Victoria University in Canada, he said, "Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when the wiggling of its tail was directed to the left rather than the right, instead of becoming alarmed, – the opposite behavior towards Italian research."
He said that differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in films or robot dogs as dogs.
A useful study of how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
"While there is sufficient evidence for different mammals that two brain hemispheres are used for different purposes, many details have yet to be specified, and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
