The scream of Obama's voter's despair
I voted for President Obama twice, sharing the hope of change.
He says that Obama allowed Republican obstructionism to derail commendable efforts.
Obstructionism cannot justify problems with Obama's reformed health system website, drone attacks
The 2008 Obama campaign memoirs are a sad reminder of what might have been
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard University School of Medicine.
I'm reading a terribly sad book these days.
I thought this book would inspire me in times of discouragement in the second year of medical school and give me a renewed sense of hope.
It is called "Dirty for Victory", and these are memoirs about Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish writing reports on my patients at night and go to bed, this book brings me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and performances could be breathtaking.
The election victory was impressive, and news hosts paused to reflect on this historic moment.
My classmates were crying out of joy, and my parents were saving every newspaper they could find.
A young team of strategists would come to the White House, and the people were ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, his level of support was 82%.
Then I close the book.
Return to the present is a rough awakening, like pulling out of a dream.
It is hard to remember those days of optimism — they seem a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I omitted my first ballot, changes have indeed taken place.
It was something I couldn't imagine.
I commend Obama for his great and varied achievements, from the adoption of the law on affordable medical care to the withdrawal of our military from Iraq, the lifting of the rule of "Don't ask, don't tell", the killing of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructionism has blocked too many attempts to move our country forward: immigration reform, public health choices and the closure of the Guantanamo base, among others.
But after countless times, when I sided with the Obama administration to protect it in front of colleagues and peers, I ran out of explanations I can offer.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain permission to listen to foreign leaders or drone strikes on innocent children in other countries.
He cannot explain the collection of data on the privacy of Americans by the National Security Agency or the pursuit of whistleblowers who reveal government misconduct.
He cannot explain the murder of an American citizen, Anwar al-Awlaki, without trial, or the failure to comply with State funding and spending limits during the presidential campaigns.
He cannot justify the report's conclusions, which states that the White House's efforts to silence the media have been "the most aggressive... since the Nixon administration."
More recently, it cannot justify failing to develop a simple web site for more than three years after the signing of the law on affordable health care.
I don't know if I should have expected that.
Should I have understood at the age of 18 that the leadership could contradict the political campaigns that precede it?
It is clear that elected office is not a predictable programme of action, as our public dialogue will be formed by an opposition political party and by random events such as the massacre in Newtown.
Nevertheless, it is evident from all the examples I have cited above that they were to a large extent a choice of their own by the Administration.
And that's what worries me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was an obscure and crude alternative, and seemed unable to make a decision on his own policies or views.
I believed that in his second term, Obama, free from the pressures of future elections, would live up to the hopes we have heard of for so long.
However, when Obama's rating dropped below 45% this week, it became much more difficult to return to 2008 through this book.
It makes me long for a lot of promises that have gone away.
This week, I read the part of the book that describes how Clinton stunned Obama in the Pennsylvania primary election.
At a meeting to analyse the causes of failure, he told his staff that they must return to normal and remain true to their purpose.
"I want us to return our attractiveness," he said.
- We must remember who we are."
It's been five years, Mr. President, and I totally agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are exclusively those of Nathaniel Morris.
