Mohammed Mursi takes the oath, but the day of his celebration is unlikely to mark the end of Egypt's political struggle.
ISLAMIC Mohammed Morsi promised a "new Egypt" when he sworn in, becoming the country's first freely elected president, replacing Hosni Mubarak, who was overthrown 16 months ago.
In his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Mursi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and the fifth head of State in Egypt after the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He took an oath in front of 18 judges in black robes in a courthouse on the shore of the Nile built in the style of an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We seek a better future, a new Egypt and a second republic," Mursi said during a solemn ceremony aired live on state television.
"Today, the Egyptian people laid the foundations of a new life — absolute freedom, genuine democracy and stability," Morsi said, a 60-year-old engineer with an American entity from the Muslim Brothers, a fundamentalist group that for most of its 84 years was a banned organization that was the target of the harsh actions of successive governments.
The building was guarded by hundreds of soldiers and policemen when Morsi arrived with a small convoy shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered at the courthouse to welcome the new president, and unlike the Mubarak-era presidential pomp, the movement was stopped only for a short time to miss his convoy on a normally busy road connecting the city's centre to the southern suburbs.
Although Mursi was ridiculed as a non-charismatic "reserve wheel" of the Brothers, his personal prestige has grown sharply since his victory and Friday speech, in which he attempted to present himself as a candidate not only for Islamists, but also for all those who want to complete the 2011 uprising against authoritarian Mubarak.
