Travel through mud, rivers and jungle to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free medical care in rural areas in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend receiving hundreds of patients.
There are not many doctors in this West African country — only one per 5,000 people.
Vote here or through your mobile device.
Dr Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 main characters of the 2013 CNN.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main heroes to make him the CNN Hero of the Year.
This man will get $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwell saw his father return to life and return to unconsciousness, wandering through hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, his arm was only broken, but the infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that resembled herself for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwell.
If we had the money, we'd get him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwell accompanied his father for years in overcrowded clinics and hospitals, receiving any treatment they might have received.
"It's not easy," Bwelle said.
- You can leave the house at 5:00 a.m., run to the hospital to be first, but you're not the first.
There's a lot of patients.
Some may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation has not changed much since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if the Cameroonians could see a doctor, many of them wouldn't be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and almost three quarters of health spending in the country is private.
"His only problem is poverty," Bwelle said.
- And because of poverty, they can't enjoy their lives."
Seeing his father's suffering and so many of his compatriots, Bwell was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers conducted 700 free operations.
He himself became a doctor and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes weekend trips to rural areas to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people are forced into vans, tied to the roofs by medical supplies and travelling across the border to visit villages in need of assistance.
They're not always lucky.
They've had to push cars through rivers and mud many times.
But when they arrive, they are greeted as real heroes: it is a festival with songs and dances and the best facilities the locals can offer.
Free health care in these villages is indeed a cause for celebration, and Bwelle, with his broad smile and unlimited energy, is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning, the brigade begins receiving hundreds of patients.
"We accept 500 people on every trip," Bwell said.
They come from the entire county within a radius of 60 kilometres of the village, and they walk.
Each of these clinics provides a variety of health services on a day off basis.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates — documents needed for the school that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the brigade conducts simple operations under local anaesthesia.
Operations are generally conducted in a school, municipality or home building; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the post-op area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to light the operating and sanitary treatment of equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers operate until early Sunday morning.
It's too fast, but the team's commitment usually helps to support the village musicians.
"They hit drums all night to keep us awake and working," Bwell said.
On Sunday, members of the brigade go back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students, conducted 700 free operations last year, and they know that their assistance can be of great importance to those they help.
One person explained that his free hernia treatment surgery would allow him to work again.
"It will change the future for me and my family," said the man.
In addition to these weekend clinical treatments and working at the hospital as a surgeon, Bwell also works nights at private medical clinics around Yaoundé.
It was this second job, he said, that provided 60% of the funding for his non-profit organization; the rest was covered by private donations.
"I don't even know when he's sleeping," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in Bwell's band.
He's always in the hospital, or he's trying to make money for the organization to keep these campaigns going.
For future doctors and nurses, such as O'Malley, coming from the United States and Europe to join Bwell in his tasks, it is an opportunity for practice that they would never get at home.
"We were given the opportunity to assist in operations where we helped remove blood stains or hold tools for Dr. Bwell," O'Malley said.
As a sophomore student, you would never get that opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medicines.
But on arrival in Yaoundé, their meals, transportation and training are paid for by Bwell.
"He's a hero, no doubt," O'Malley said.
He gave his life to that organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon was endless.
For Bwell, an almost constant workload is not a heavy test.
Helping others to live a happy life, fulfilling their father’s promise, is what brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy doing this job," Bwelle said.
- And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Go to the ASCOVIME website and see what you can do.
