The Rosbalt Agency revoked media status for uncensored war
On October 31, Moshorsud decided to invalidate the Rosbalt Agency's registration licence, writes Lenta.
Roscomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of media status, for systematic and gross violations of the media law.
In the course of the trial, an unpleasant precedent was set: the court considered it possible to close the media, effectively denying the publication the right to counter-arguments.
What's "Rosbalt"
The Rosbalt Information Agency was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also has offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and operated as a federal information and analysis agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private Internet SMI in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency's exclusive publications were (and still are) notes referring to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the proximity of the publication to the power structures continued throughout the Agency's existence.
While Rosbalt had an extensive source base in various agencies, it was also suggested that Natalia Chaplin, the wife of Victor Cherkesov, was in charge of the project.
However, Chaplin's role in the management of the Rosbalt is not fully clear: she is most often referred to as the “project manager”.
Larissa Afonin is the director-general of the agency and editor-in-chief, Nikolai Ulyanov.
In recent times, Rosbalt has not featured in federal media ratings - either by quote or audience.
In October, the agency ranked 25th in the attendance rating of Russian media websites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the website rosbalt.ru is about 150,000 unique visitors (and up to 500,000 views), and the monthly audience is about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials in the last five months are notes on the Kremlin's powerlessness with Ukraine, the death of the band's soloist King and Fool, and the pogroms in the Metropolitan Biryulev.
Rosbalt's conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the Media Act came into force prohibiting journalists from engaging in uncensored fighting.
The agency found banned lexics in two videos published on the agency's website ("Gigit of Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot desecrated oil towers").
The other parties describe in different ways.
Roscomnadzor accused Rosbalt of a gross and systematic violation of the media law on the basis of video footage and requested the court to withdraw the agency's licence.
Rosbalt stated that the agency's claims were wrong: first, the videos were not editorial material; secondly, the mother's words in them were disguised; and thirdly, the videos were removed from the site immediately after warning.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor ' s claims to the Peace Court - and when Moshorsud accepted Roskomnadzor ' s claim on 22 October 2013, the complaints were still pending.
However, on the 25th, the justice of the peace had ruled against Rosbalt: editor-in-chief Nikolai Uljanov had been found guilty of violating the Code of Administrative Offences and fined 20,000 rubles - 10,000 each for each video.
Obviously, this prejudged the outcome of the Moshorsud hearing - if you give up the thought that the outcome might have been prejudged earlier.
On 31 October, the court decided to invalidate the Rosbalt registration certificate, effectively depriving the agency of media status.
It is not possible to say that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The Agency supported the deputies of the State Duma (an application to the head of Roscomnadzor, Alexander Jarov, signed 26 deputies on 10 October; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the CRC).
The President of the Union of Journalists of Russia, Vsevolod Bogdanov, Pavel Gusev, Chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists, and Mikhail Fedotov, Head of the Presidential Council for Human Rights, claimed that the publication had been illegal.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, Roscomnadzor's leadership even provided him with some assurance that it would not come to an end before the licence was withdrawn.
The Rosbalt trial showed that under whose jurisdiction the media in Russia is safer today is a big question.
