Australian woman appeals against imprisonment in Thailand
A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, sentenced to 15 days in prison on Phuket Island for falsely claiming that she had been attacked by a taxi driver, appealed the sentence and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty by the Phuket Provincial Court on 15 June of filing a false lawsuit following a report by Thai police that a local taxi driver had carried out an attack on the night of Sunday 10 June, while two other men held her.
However, video surveillance footage later revealed that she had returned safely to her hotel after breaking her relationship with her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police questioned Bamford for two days before she admitted to fabricating the story.
Prior to the trial, she was held in local police cells.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a general-security detention centre on the outskirts of Phuketa, rather than in a women's adult prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian League player Peter Tanks, who applied to the Department of Foreign Affairs in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tanks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the entire family was "extremely concerned" about its daughter's well-being and waited for her to return to Australia.
"It is obvious that this was an alarming time, but we hope that she will return home safely as soon as possible," Tanks said.
Bamford appealed her sentence and was released on bail at 50,000 baht.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently on vacation in the Craby Resort Area in southern Thailand.
Legal sources in Thailand reported that Bamford was currently represented by a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that an appeal could result in the court increasing her sentence to two years and forcing her to serve her sentence in an adult prison.
However, following the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore its damaged tourist image, leading to acquittal.
